occurrences.line_text: Who for the proofe of his great puissance,
To deedes of armes and proofe of cheualrie
For proofe shew forth thy sword, and let it tell,
For proofe whereof, he bad them Florimell forth call.
And battailes doubtfull proofe their rights to try,
But lastly to make proofe of vtmost shame,
Ere proofe it tooke, discouered was betymes,
The proofe of battell, now in doubtfull night,
Let her by proofe of that, which she hath fylde
And proou'd your strength on a strong enimie,
Againe his wonted angry weapon proou'd:
Then all the world, when euer it were proou'd;
So proou'd it eke that gracious God of wine,
And to her bed approching, first she prooued,
I chaunst to see her in her proper hew,
Proper to gentle bloud; some others faine
In Claribellaes clothes. Her proper face
And gainst the Romanes bent their proper powre,
Where each might best offend his proper part,
That in their proper prayse too partiall bee,
To let him loose, to saue their proper stakes;
Out of their proper places farre away,
Nor tooke away his loue, but his owne proper good.
Of their vaine prowesse, turned to their proper bale.
To leaue his proper forme, and other shape to take.
An ambling Colt, that is his proper owne:
And at the last breake forth in his owne proper kynd.
Vpon your seas, he claym'd as propertie:
And that old man Eumnestes, by their propertis.
Which mote not be prophan'd of common eyes,
A sacrament prophane in mistery of wine.
Of gold, that bad eyes might it not prophane:
And which all Asia sought with vowes prophane,
That Proteus prophecide should him dismay,
(For Proteus was with prophecie inspir'd)
It was no time to scan the prophecie,
Thereto he was expert in prophecies,
Fond Proteus, father of false prophecis,
Well hop't he then, when this was propheside,
Shewes, visions, sooth-sayes, and prophesies;
With that the Prophet still awhile did stay,
The hellish Harpies, prophets of sad destiny.
Yet sleeping, in his well proportiond face,
Proportioned equally by seuen and nine;
Those two the first and last proportions are,
The which, for all the suit I could propound,
To follow that, which he did long propound;
But these conditions doe to him propound,
Began the streight conditions to propound,
With these conditions, which I will propound:
Which he so wisely well did prosecute,
From prosecuting his reuenging rage;
From prosecuting of her first intent,
And sad Proserpina the Queene of hell;
The Gardin of Proserpina this hight;
Brought thee from balefull house of Proserpine,
And sad Proserpines wrath, them to affright.
For th'heauens enuying our prosperitie,
That enuies louers long prosperity,
And all prostrate vpon the lowly plaine,
Whose carcases on ground were horribly prostrate.
And perfect hole, prostrate she fell vnto the ground.
Before faire Britomart, she fell prostrate,
She did prostrate, and with right humble hart,
Whylest kings and kesars at her feet did them prostrate.
I giue thee life: therefore prostrated fall,
Whom when he saw before his foote prostrated,
And her proud person low prostrated on the plaine.
But Belge with her sonnes prostrated low
Whom when he saw prostrated on the plaine,
And him before themselues prostrating low,
And on the ground her selfe prostrating low,
Was all abasht, and low prostrating, said;
And by your powre protect his feeble cace.
That seemed nought could him from death protect:
All these I wote in thy protection bee,
Had left in his protection whileare,
Seem'd vnder her protection him to shroud;
The eldest Gonorill gan to protest,
As euer Proteus to himselfe could make:
One day of Proteus by his mightie spell,
(For Proteus was with prophecie inspir'd)
That Proteus prophecide should him dismay,
Fond Proteus, father of false prophecis,
Who wrongd by Carle by Proteus sau'd,
With shrilling shriekes, Proteus abroad did roue,
Proteus is Shepheard of the seas of yore,
Was Florimell, when Proteus she did see thereby.
he comes to Proteus hall,
Vnlouely Proteus, missing to his mind
Should for the Gods in Proteus house be made;
All these together marched toward Proteus hall.
That Proteus house they fild euen to the dore;
To Proteus selfe to sue for her discharge:
Her forth to fetch, and Proteus to constraine:
Whether old Proteus true or false had sayd,
To Proteus selfe to sew she thought it vaine,
Proteus, that hath ordayn'd my sonne to die;
Commaunding Proteus straight t'enlarge the mayd,
Departed straight to Proteus therewithall:
Who being freed from Proteus cruell band
Swift Proto, milde Eucrate, Thetis faire,
And Panopï¿½, and wise Protomedï¿½a,
The sayling Pine, the Cedar proud and tall,
At last it chaunced this proud Sarazin
Who whiles he liu'de, was called proud Sans foy,
Whose yeelded pride and proud submission,
And mightie proud to humble weake does yield,
But that proud Paynim forward came so fierce,
Proud of such glory and aduancement vaine,
So proud she shyned in her Princely state,
And proud Lucifera men did her call,
Of proud Lucifera, and his owne companie.
Of proud Lucifer', as one of the traine:
With proud foes sight my sorrow to renew:
For with that Pagan proud he combat will that day.
And to him said, Goe now proud Miscreant,
They were by law of that proud Tyrannesse
There was that great proud king of Babylon,
And proud Antiochus, the which aduaunst
Proud Tarquin, and too lordly Lentulus,
Proud wemen, vaine, forgetfull of their yoke:
Whereas that Pagan proud him selfe did rest,
Whom all so soone as that proud Sarazin
Fled farre away, of that proud Paynim sore afrayd.
By Gyaunt proud opprest,
And after him the proud Duessa came,
Came ramping forth with proud presumpteous gate,
The proud Duessa full of wrathfull spight,
That of his puissance proud ensample made;
Whom when his maistresse proud perceiu'd to fall,
Whose prouder vaunt that proud auenging boy
For she was proud, and of too high intent,
His daintie corse, proud humors to abate,
Yet had he prou'd the powre of many a puissant knight.
Such proud luxurious pompe is swollen vp but late.
Gainst that proud Paynim king, that workes her teene:
Sith her Prince Arthur of proud ornaments
Who so in pompe of proud estate (quoth she)
Depart to woods vntoucht, & leaue so proud disdaine?
The Maide[n]; proud through prayse, and mad through loue
And stoutly prou'd thy puissaunce here in sight;
His proud presumed force increased more,
Your selfe his prowesse prou'd & found him fiers & bold.
And match his brother proud in battailous array.
At proud Cymochles, whiles his shield was wyde,
Nor that proud towre of Troy, though richly guilt,
The king returned proud of victorie,
Fro[m] Guendolene his wife, though alwaies faithfull prou'd.
Through proud ambition, against her rebeld,
His brother Morgan, prickt with proud disdaine,
Then Ruddoc and proud Stater, both allyes,
Next Archigald, who for his proud disdaine,
Stoupes at a flying heron with proud disdaine,
And the great sea puft vp with proud disdaine,
Of their proud beautie, and th'one moyity
As the proud Persian Queenes accustomed:
And her proud portance, and her princely gest,
And his proud foes discomfit in victorious field.
Proud Etheldred shall from the North arise,
Proud Sisera, and how Camill' hath slaine
Ythrild with deepe disdaine of his proud threat,
Proud of his dying honor and deare bands,
So fell proud Marinell vpon the pretious shore.
And with proud enuy, and indignant ire,
Which as a victour proud, gan ransack fast
In his proud furnitures she freshly dight,
Proud Braggadocchio, that in vaunting vaine
Proud man himselfe then Braggadocchio deemed,
At those proud words that other knight begonne
The roaring billowes in their proud disdaine,
Is the late ruine of proud Marinell,
Where proud Encelade, whose wide nosethrils burnd
And many fortunes prou'd in th'Ocean mayne,
She proud of that new honour, which they red,
Whiles the proud Bird ruffing his fethers wyde,
More sundry colours, then the proud Pauone
And their proud girlonds of tryumphant bayes
Nought therewith daunted was her courage proud,
That his proud spoyle of that same dolorous
Of which full proud, himselfe vp rearing hye,
Nathlesse proud man himselfe the other deemed,
And prou'd himselfe most foole, in what he seem'd most wise.
Well said the wiseman, now prou'd true by this,
Yet did this trustie Squire with proud disdaine
But the proud Nymph would for no worldly meed,
Proud Priams towne. So wise is Nereus old,
Proud of his Adamants, with which he shines
Which the proud Humber vnto them had donne,
White hand Eunica, proud Dynamene,
Well prou'd in that same day, when Ioue those Gyants quelled.
All sixe well seene in armes, and prou'd in many a fight.
With proud disdaine did scornefull answere make;
But the proud boaster gan his doome vpbrayd,
That a proud Amazon did late defy
Any her proud obseruaunce will withstand,
Her proud foote setting, at his head did leuell,
With stately port and proud magnificence,
There bound t'obay that Amazons proud law,
Seruing proud Radigund with true subiection;
She gan to stoupe, and her proud mind conuert
And proud rebellious flesh to mortify.
At last proud Radigund with fell despight,
And her proud person low prostrated on the plaine.
Whom that proud Amazon subdewed had,
By that proud dame, which her so much disdained,
Where soone as his proud wife of her had sight,
For the proud Souldan with presumpteous cheare,
Of that proud Souldan, whom he earst did slay.
Who came at length, with proud presumpteous gate,
Glad to be quit from that proud Tyrants awe,
And proud despight of his selfe pleasing mynd,
And is the boast of that proud Ladies threat,
But put away proud looke, and vsage sterne,
A proud discourteous knight:
Wherewith he wroth, and full of proud disdaine,
Or through support of count'nance proud and hault
Where that proud Knight in his presumption
And this proud gyant should with braue emprize
He would auenge th'abuses of that proud
Pursuing that proud Knight, the which whileare
But she thereof grew proud and insolent,
That such proud looks would make her praysed more;
For penaunce of my proud and hard rebellious hart.
That could so meekly make proud hearts auale,
And now haue prou'd, what happineesse ye hold
And prou'd the perfect pleasures, which doe grow
Or haue ye yeelded you to proude oppression
But this proude Dame disdayning all accord,
And when him list the prouder lookes subdew,
Whose prouder vaunt that proud auenging boy
Then which a prouder Lady liueth none:
Performd, in paragone of proudest men:
Their tawney bodies, in their proudest plight:
And sooth oft seene, that proudest harts base loue hath blynded.
Vnder his Lordly foot him proudly hath supprest.
And proudly said, Lo there the worthie meed
Proudly to prune, and set on euery side,
So proudly pricketh on his courser strong,
Which proudly did impugne her sentence iust.
Proudly stands ouer, and a while doth pause,
For I him find to be too proudly fed.
Eftsoones forth pricked proudly in his might,
To proue his puissance in battell braue
To proue his sense, and tempt her faigned truth.
That doth this Redcrosse knights ensample plainly proue.
To proue the wide report of her great Maiestee.
But ioyd weake wemens hearts to tempt, and proue
And proue thy puissaunt armes, as seemes thee best became.
He, now to proue his late renewed might,
To proue how many acres he did spread of land.
Her feeble pulse, to proue if any drop
He pricked forth, his puissant force to proue,
But sith in might thou didst my mercy proue,
To proue extremities of bloudie fight,
To proue he liued ill, that did thus foully dye.
At last resolu'd likewise to proue the rest,
And proue his cause. With that her mortall speare
Too well we see, (said they) and proue too well
Which I to proue, this voyage haue begonne.
That well can witnesse, who by triall it does proue.
Or proue thy selfe, this sad encounter shonne,
To proue some deedes of armes vpon an equall pere.
Therewith resolu'd to proue her vtmost might,
As he did for Erigone it proue,)
A thousand charmes he formerly did proue;
That both resolu'd the last extremities to proue.
But whosoeuer contrarie doth proue,
Likewise assayd, to proue that girdles powre;
Without displeasance for to proue his spere.
Where she captiued long, great woes did proue;
I me resolu'd the vtmost end to proue,
Which losse her made like passion also proue.
Would change his liking, and new Lemans proue:
As when an eager mastiffe once doth proue
That if old sawes proue true (which God forbid)
Which well I proue, as shall appeare by triall,
To proue her surname true, that she imposed has.
Against him iustifie, and proue her cleare
To proue if better foote then horsebacke would ensew.
And proue the finall fortune of the fight:
In hope he sure would proue a doughtie knight:
In th'end his kyndly courtesie to proue,
And proue thy manhood on the billowes vayne.
Small praise to proue your powre on wight so weake.
So mighty blowes, or proue the puissaunce of his pride.
Yet ceast he not to sew and all waies proue,
So shew'd them her, to proue how pale & weake she was.
Yet pittie in her hart was neuer proued
And his well proued weapons to him hent;
For his great vertues proued long afore:
Last turne was mine, well proued to my paine,
As if some proued perill he did feare,
Through his too ventrous prowesse proued ouer all.
And swat, and chauf'd, and proued euery way:
And with wide glauncing words, one day she thus him proued.
For so great prowesse, as he there had proued,
And proued oft in many perillous fight,
The proued powre of noble Calidore,
But thou his errour shalt, I hope now prouen trew.
Their bodies to his beasts for prouender did spred.
With which my weaker patience fortune proues.
The housling fire did kindle and prouide,
For which Dan Phebus selfe cannot a salue prouide.
Till time for him should remedy prouide,
Hath he her lent, a Champion to prouide?
Which to prouide, she hath this Castle dight,
Prouided him a sword of meanest sort:
Eternall prouidence exceeding thought,
Led with eternall prouidence, that has
Prouidence heauenly passeth liuing thought,
You send, submit you to high prouidence,
Corineus had that Prouince vtmost west,
Least suddaine mischiefe ye too rash prouoke:
Nor too much to prouoke; for he would learne
Ne chaffar words, prowd courage to prouoke,
Him all that while Occasion did prouoke
It seemes, iust wrongs to vengeance doe prouoke,
Not to prouoke misfortune, nor to weene
What monstrous enmity prouoke we heare,
Ne list I for reuenge prouoke new fight,
Which Britomart him gaue, when he did her prouoke.
Prouoked them the breaches to assay,
Whose sharpe prouokement them incenst so sore,
Prouoking him by her outrageous talke,
And rash prouoking perils all about,
Prouokt with VVrath, and Enuies false surmise,
For death was due to him, that had prouokt Gods ire.
But still prouokt her sonne to wreake her wrong;
False Archimage prouokt their courage prowd,
And Ate eke prouokt him priuily,
He is prouokt, and stird vp day and night
But where he is prouokt with peeuishnesse,
In hope there for his loue some succour to prouyde.
Would for the wretched infants helpe prouyde,
Some of borne brethren, prov'd vnnaturall;
Got these three louely babes, that prov'd three cha[m]pions bold.
Vpon them gladly would haue prov'd his might,
Where also proofe of thy prow valiaunce
And that great Princesse too exceeding prowd,
Thereat the Scarcrow wexed wondrous prowd,
Ne chaffar words, prowd courage to prouoke,
A prowd rebellious Vnicorne defies,
False Archimage prouokt their courage prowd,
Till the prowd Romanes him disquieted,
The warlike virgine seeing his so prowd
And prowdly threw to ground, as things of naught;
For onely worthy you through prowes priefe
Or that your prowesse can me yield reliefe:
Yet of his prowesse proofe he since hath made
Can speake his prowesse, that did earst you beare,
Mongst many, one that with his prowesse may
Wondrous great prowesse and heroick worth
Ne ought the prayse of prowesse more doth marre,
Through deedes of armes and prowesse martiall;
Your selfe his prowesse prou'd & found him fiers & bold.
Ne canst of prowesse, ne of knighthood deeme,
And left two sonnes, of pearelesse prowesse both;
Of their braue gestes and prowesse martiall;
Whose prowesse paragon saw neuer liuing wight.
And noble prowesse, which they had approued,
Who through great prowesse and bold hardinesse,
Which I your vassall, by your prowesse freed,
But that his vtmost prowesse there made knowen,
The prayse of prowesse from them all away.
After the proofe of prowesse ended well,
Through his too ventrous prowesse proued ouer all.
But second vnto none in prowesse prayse;
The greater prowesse greater perils find.
Of their vaine prowesse, turned to their proper bale.
For so great prowesse, as he there had proued,
Yet haue, through prowesse and their braue emprize,
And loued for his prowesse, sith they twaine
The prowest knight, that euer field did fight,
And to him running said, O prowest knight,
For they be two the prowest knights on ground,
Vnmindfull of thy praise and prowest might,
For yonder comes the prowest knight aliue,
Faire mote he thee, the prowest and most gent,
Proofe be thou Prince, the prowest man aliue,
To loue the prowest knight, that euer was.
Two of the prowest Knights in Faery lond;
Such as that prudent Romane well inuented,
Proudly to prune, and set on euery side,
To plant or prune: for of their owne accord
Hath pruned from the natiue tree, and cropped quight.
She fownd not in that perilous house of Pryde,
Till prickt with courage, and thy forces pryde,
From chase of greater beasts, whose brutish pryde
Then Paridell, in whom a kindly pryde
How towards her he rusht, and smiled at his pryde.
At Artegall, in middest of his pryde,
Myld Titus and Gesippus without pryde;
Where that discourteous Dame with scornfull pryde,
Another knight in his despiteous pryde;
But laught them out, as if his greater pryde
To be the man, that with such scornefull pryde
But stout Despetto in his greater pryde,
Eftsoones they pricked forth with forward pryde,
He scorned in his ouerweening pryde;
So fell those two in spight of both their prydes,
He woo'd her thus: Pryene (so she hight)
That was Pryene; she did first offend,
Nathlesse his pride full dearely he did pryse;
Or such as that celestiall Psalmist was,
And Psamathe, for her brode snowy brests;
And his true loue faire Psyche with him playes,
Faire Psyche to him lately reconcyld,
Pleasure, the daughter of Cupid and Psyche late.
And vnto Psyche with great trust and care
That learned Ptolomaee his hight did take,
Great Ptolomï¿½e it for his lemans sake
Matilda, daughter to Pubidius,
Both of their publicke praise had them despoyled,
Importune care of their owne publicke cause;
Amongst fraile men, that many a publike state
A solemne feast, with publike turneying,
And take great ioy to publish it to many,
Of muddie water, that like puddle stanke;
In which a puddle of contagion was,
For not one puffe of wind there did appeare,
Loosely disperst with puffe of euery blast:
If any puffe of breath, or signe of sence she fand.
At puffe of euery storme doth stagger here and theare.
That ouersprad her like a puffe of wind;
That puffed vp with smoke of vanitie,
Puft vp with emptie wind, and fild with sinfull crime.
And the great sea puft vp with proud disdaine,
To proue his puissance in battell braue
Quoth she, his princely puissance doth abate,
Yet so great was the puissance of his push,
Of saluage beast, his puissance to withstand:
That of his puissance proud ensample made;
Almightie God her gaue such powre, and puissance great.
That nothing seemd the puissance could withstand:
That nought so wondrous puissance might sustaine;
Or else his wrong with greater puissance maintaine.
They were two knights of perelesse puissance,
That of his puissance tryall made extreeme;
That in aduauntage would his puissance bost:
That neither could his mightie puissance sustaine.
And eke in semblance of his puissance great,
Thus these twelue troupes with dreadfull puissance
Then he with all his puissance doth striue
That mortall puissance mote not withstond:
Their puissance, whylome full dernely tryde:
So long as breath, and hable puissance
Thy dayes abridge, through proofe of puissance,
The puissance of his intended stroke.
Who for the proofe of his great puissance,
His puissance, ne beare him selfe vpright,
And then the Gyant stroue with puissance strong
And at her strooke with puissance fearefull fell;
But he me first, through pride and puissance strong
Their puissant force, and cruell rage attonce,
Of puissant armes, and laid in easie bed;
Yet sore amoued with so puissant push,
Yet had he prou'd the powre of many a puissant knight.
He pricked forth, his puissant force to proue,
So puissant foe, with enuious despight
Or think, that ought those puissant hands may marre:
His poinant speare he thrust with puissant sway
Oppressours powre by armes and puissant hond?
Adowne he kest it with so puissant wrest,
Tho vp he caught him twixt his puissant hands,
And on his collar laying puissant hand,
Three such as able were to match a puissant host.
For that with puissant stroke she downe did beare
Of puissant Nations, which the world possest;
For that he is so puissant and strong,
And for to maister wrong and puissant pride,
Albe the stroke so strong and puissant were,
Each others equall puissaunce enuies,
Whom great Orgoglio with his puissaunce fell
And stoutly prou'd thy puissaunce here in sight;
To thinke, such hideous puissaunce on foot to beare.
As well in state of peace, as puissaunce in warre.
For with such puissaunce and impetuous maine
Of warlike puissaunce in ages spent,
Great aid thereto his mighty puissaunce,
Of his late puissaunce, his Image dead,
Consume, till all their warlike puissaunce be spent.
Yet these, and all that else had puissaunce,
With so fierce furie and great puissaunce,
T'employ her puissaunce to his reskew,
So mighty blowes, or proue the puissaunce of his pride.
Putting his puissaunce forth, pursu'd so hard,
And proue thy puissaunt armes, as seemes thee best became.
Ah puissaunt Lords, what cursed euill Spright,
His puissaunt armes about his noble brest,
Vnder Sir Guyons puissaunt stroke to fall,
Three times more furious, and more puissaunt,
And puissaunt kings, which all the world warrayd,
Her Steed did stagger with that puissaunt strooke;
But hayld and puld with all his might and maine,
That may pull downe the courage of his pride;
Vntill that state by strength was pulled downe,
He pulleth downe, he setteth vp on hy;
Her feeble pulse, to proue if any drop
With trembling hand his troubled pulse gan try;
